ofibular ligament is one of the lateral ligaments of the ankle, playing a crucial role in stabilising the joint. It connects the fibula to the calcaneus and is often involved in ankle sprains.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA tear in the \u003Cstrong\u003Ecalcaneofibular ligament\u003C/strong\u003E primarily affects the stability of the ankle during \u003Cstrong\u003Einversion\u003C/strong\u003E movements. This ligament is part of the lateral ligament complex of the ankle and provides resistance against excessive inversion. When it is torn, the ankle becomes more prone to inversion injuries, leading to instability.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlantarflexion\u003C/strong\u003E - This movement is primarily controlled by the muscles of the posterior compartment of the leg\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDorsiflexion\u003C/strong\u003E - This movement is primarily controlled by the muscles of the anterior compartment of the leg\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEversion\u003C/strong\u003E - This movement is resisted by the deltoid ligament on the medial side of the ankle\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbduction\u003C/strong\u003E - This movement is not significantly affected by the calcaneofibular ligament\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The calcaneofibular ligament is one of the lateral ligaments of the ankle.","A tear in the calcaneofibular ligament can lead to instability during inversion of the foot.","The calcaneofibular ligament helps to stabilize the ankle joint, particularly during movements that involve inversion."],"references":["Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Smith, R., 